ly to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John FitzHerbert was born before 1190, in Norbury, Derbyshire, England, his father, John Fitz-Herbert, was 11186 and his mother, Agnes de Stretton, was 27. He married Emmeline de Grendon before 1210, in Norbury, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after 1228, in his hometown."},"et":{"before 1190–AFT 1228":"enne 1190–pärast 1228","1190–1228":"1190–1228","1211–Male":"1211–Surnud","1175–1228":"1175–1228","1210–1280":"1210–1280","1220–1274":"1220–1274","1170